insert into articles (category, title, content, createdBy, lastUpdated, coverPhoto) values
(1, '5 Great Alternatives to the Colour Magenta', '<p>If you''re a designer, chances are that at some point in your life you&rsquo;ve been tasked with creating something in the colour magenta. Whether it has been an advertisement or a website design, or perhaps even just a banner for your company''s social media account, there is no denying that it can be hard to find other colours which match well with this bright purple hue. But don''t worry! It doesn''t have to be difficult to find five colours that will go well with this shade of purple.</p>
<p>Here are our top picks: fuchsia, raspberry pink, deep violet, lavender and burgundy red. Which one do you like best?</p>
<p><strong>Fuchsia</strong></p>
<p>Fuchsia is a bright, warm colour that is similar in hue to magenta. It''s an energetic and fun shade that can be used well in many design projects. In addition, it can fit very well with a lot of other vibrant colours. This rich and dark purple has some similarities with magenta in terms of both hue and vibrancy. However, it has some blue undertones which really set it apart from this famously more purple shade.</p>
<p>This extremely dark red hue is almost closer to black than it is to any other colour. It''s another great alternative because of how different it is from the traditional purplish shades, but still has some similarity with magenta in terms of vibrancy and saturation.</p>
<p><strong>Raspberry Pink</strong></p>
<p>Another bright and warm colour, raspberry pink is just on the opposite side of the spectrum from magenta/fuchsia. It''s a great alternative to magenta as it feels just as strong and bold as this purple, but without being too similar in its shade or hue.</p>
<p>Paired with a bright, white background, raspberry pink is a great way to create a fun and colourful website design. It will also contrast magenta brilliantly while still looking professional.</p>
<p>Raspberry pink is the ideal substitute for the colour magenta if you are looking for something with an antique or vintage feel to it. This soft pink hue has been described by some as being ''dusty'' or ''dirty''.</p>
<p><strong>Deep Violet</strong></p>
<p>Deep violet is another alternative to the colour magenta which is cool in its effect. If you wanted to use purple but didn''t want something too bright, this would be a good choice.</p>
<p>Deep violet can easily go hand-in-hand with magenta. It is also described as being deep in comparison to lighter purples, so it stands out better than these alternatives when next to this same shade of purple.</p>
<p><strong>Lavender</strong></p>
<p>Lavender is similar in hue to lavender, which makes it another very relaxing shade of purple that works well with many other colours because of its subdued brightness.</p>
<p>Lavender can work well with magenta, despite typically being used alongside other shades like blue and green rather than purples. It is a soft shade that will work well if you want to use purple without going too far into the ''bright and bold'' territory.</p>
<p>If you''re looking for something more vibrant than lavender but not as bright as fuchsia or raspberry pink, this would be a good choice as its hue falls somewhere between these two colours on the spectrum.</p>
<p><strong>Burgundy Red</strong></p>
<p>Another thing that makes burgundy red such a good substitute for magenta is that it can sometimes appear pink rather than red.</p>
<p>Burgundy red has more blue than magenta, which makes it muted and darker than blonde hair dye and can therefore be used well when you want to use magenta without going too bright or bold.</p>
<p>Hope that these alternatives to the electric purple shade of magenta help you in your future design projects! By keeping in mind all of the different shades of purple around, it becomes much easier to find exactly what you''re looking for when trying to avoid this kind of colour clashing.</p>
<p>If there is one thing that can be said about this article, it''s that there are certainly plenty of other great alternative colours out there to the colour magenta. But perhaps the best suggestion would be consider sticking entirely to brown if you really need something which contrasts well with blonde hair dye! Now that''s a good idea... right? ;)</p>', 1, datetime('2021-09-01 02:19:46'), '5-Great-Alternatives-to-the-Colour-Magenta.jpg'),

(2, 'Five Strange Things You Didn''t Know About Magpies', '<p>If you&rsquo;ve ever been in a field and heard the sound of a crow, then you know that they can be quite noisy. But if you&rsquo;re looking for something to really get your heart racing, there is nothing more terrifying than the call of the magpie. These black-and-white birds are known as &ldquo;the bringers of doom&rdquo; because their call was thought to predict death or disease. In fact, it turns out that these birds have five mysterious secrets about them which will make you think twice before going into a field again!</p>
<p><strong>1) Magpies are actually just crows with white feathers</strong></p>
<p>The magpie belongs to the same family as crows and ravens - Corvidae - and is no different from any other of its relatives. In fact, it&rsquo;s only the white colouration of the magpie that sets this bird apart - and even then, a scientist who wanted to study them would have to use maps and measurements of their distribution across the country rather than just a picture.</p>
<p><strong>2) Magpies can talk</strong></p>
<p>If you need an incentive to stay out of fields with magpies in, why not try thinking about this? The call they make sounds like &ldquo;a rusty gate&rdquo; if you want to put it bluntly (which may be why people believe such stories as those mentioned above). But their song is actually more complex than that! If you hang around long enough&mdash;and we mean a very long time&mdash;you can actually tell the different calls apart and even understand what they mean. The only problem is that magpies make about 20 different sounds, so we&rsquo;re still a long way off from being able to translate them all!</p>
<p><strong>3) Magpies have been living alongside us for longer than we think</strong></p>
<p>In days gone by, there were all kinds of tales about magpies being evil omens or harbingers of death. In fact, this bad reputation has been with them for over thousands of years. But it turns out our association with these birds was not always so negative... Magpies hardly ever attacked humans in the past &ndash; but times have changed. Today are known as something quite different: thieves! They wait until we''re not looking and then they&rsquo;ll take anything shiny or brightly colored that takes their fancy. It&rsquo;s no wonder farmers hate them so much when they steal the eggs from chickens nests and even, in some cases, break into people''s houses to steal rings and other jewels.</p>
<p><strong>4) Magpies mate for life</strong></p>
<p>Magpies will usually pair up with another magpie in their area and then move in together. Once a year in early summer they''ll build a nest together where they''ll raise their young, making them one of the few social birds which actually pull it off. The only problem is that if one of the pair dies&mdash;which happens quite often these days&mdash;the other one will most likely die of a broken heart.</p>
<p><strong>5) Magpies and crows love shiny stuff</strong></p>
<p>When they see bright and shiny objects, birds like magpies and crows can''t resist picking at them to find out what it is - even if it means breaking the item! It''s not just because they''re curious either; their beaks are actually magnetically sensitive which allows them to sense the magnetic forces that surround such objects. If you want to keep your belongings safe then it might be time for you to invest in a tin-foil hat...</p>
<p>So the next time you see a magpie in the field, don''t be too scared to go up and get a closer look - you might actually enjoy yourself!</p>', 2, datetime('2020-12-15 02:26:51'), 'Five-Strange-Things-You-Didnt-Know-About-Magpies.jpg'),

(1, '10 Reasons to Get a Magenta or a Magpie Tattoo', '<p>I am a passionate person, but on the other hand, I have this constant need to be accepted by everybody. That''s why I''m going to get a magenta or a magpie tattoo.</p>
<p><strong>1) To show my true colours</strong></p>
<p>Magentas and magpies are bright and vibrant colours that represent individuality and creativity. Did you know that 90% of tattoo parlours in the United States stock magenta or magpie ink? It''s true! There''s no need to go overseas anymore to get that perfect tattoo.</p>
<p><strong>2) To express myself</strong></p>
<p>The meaning behind tattoos is an expression of who you are as an individual - what better way than with colour?&nbsp; Magentas and magpies are a symbol of creativity, uniqueness and individuality. Tattoos are one way to express yourself. They are a symbol of uniqueness and individuality. With magenta or magpie tattoos you can look bright and vibrant.</p>
<p><strong>3) To feel special</strong></p>
<p>Getting your first tattoo can be an exhilarating experience because it feels like you''ve just made yourself part of something bigger than yourself. They also represent the desire to be free from restrictions. A lot of people have them on parts of their bodies that are easily covered, but others prefer to show them off by wearing very short skirts or shorts.</p>
<p>People with magenta or magpie tattoos always get noticed everywhere they go, because there''s only 1% of the population who has it! How many people do you think will notice your new bright colourful tattoo? It might sound like a weird idea, but if you want everybody to look at you wherever you go then this is perfect for you</p>
<p><strong>4) To own my body</strong></p>
<p>In our society, we often take ownership over things (e.g., cars, homes, clothes) that are seen as extensions of ourselves. However, we can''t take ownership of our bodies because they belong to everyone else. As long as your body is public property, you might as well decorate it yourself in a way that expresses who you truly are.</p>
<p><strong>5) To express my emotions</strong></p>
<p>The colour magenta represents happiness and joy while the colour purple symbolizes compassion and love - all things I need in this world. And magpies are a symbol of luck and happiness!</p>
<p><strong>6) Because magenta looks good with everything</strong></p>
<p>Magenta or magpie tattoos look great with both feminine outfits (e.g., skinny jeans, blouses) and masculine ones (e.g., leather jackets).&nbsp; It goes great on any skin tone, so it can be worn by both men and women. Wear them with pride!</p>
<p><strong>7) To celebrate individuality</strong></p>
<p>Individuality is about thinking for yourself instead of following the crowd or doing what everybody else does. This tattoo expresses that you are an individual who has his or her own thoughts, feelings, ideas, opinions, traditions, tastes etc. It represents being different from most others - in a good way! Most people will never understand this because they''re too afraid to stand out which is why magenta or magpie tattoos are perfect for you!</p>
<p><strong>8) To stop being so indecisive</strong></p>
<p>This one is really important - I can''t keep changing my mind about things that will have to stay with me for the rest of my life.&nbsp; I''m sick of changing my mind and making decisions over and over again. I can''t make up my mind about what clothes to wear, what coffee shop I should get a mocha from or even which flavour mocha I want in the morning!</p>
<p><strong>9) To be more creative</strong></p>
<p>When you''re too busy worrying about the placement of your tattoo, it takes away from your actual creativity and ability to focus on what you want to do in life.&nbsp; Magenta or magpie tattoos are inspired by individual creativity. People with this tattoo are always very creative, thoughtful and original thinkers!</p>
<p><strong>10) Because birds are cute</strong></p>
<p>All right, this isn''t a reason, but I don''t care because magenta magpies are the cutest!</p>
<p>You should get a magenta or magpie tattoo because it''s the coolest thing that you''ve ever done. They''re absolutely stunning to look at, they make you smile every time you see one, and everyone will be green with envy when they see your new ink!&nbsp; This is one of the best decisions anyone can make - trust me, don''t think about it anymore! Go for it!</p>
<p>REMEMBER: When deciding on your next piece of body art, choose wisely because tattoos are forever. You can never change what you get inked onto your skin!</p>', 4, datetime('2020-02-14 02:26:34'), '10-Reasons-to-Get-a-Magenta-or-a-Magpie-Tattoo.jpg'),

(2, 'How to Tell a Magpie From a Crow' ,'<p>Magpies are one of the most fascinating creatures in the world. They have so many features that make them amazing! One way you can tell if it''s a magpie or crow is by looking at their feathers under magnification. Magpies'' feathers are thicker and more rounded, while crows'' are thinner and pointer, just like needles! There are also other ways to tell which bird is what, but this is one of the easiest methods. You should take notes on these differences because they could come in handy someday!</p>
<p><strong>What are the differences between magpies and crows?</strong></p>
<p>There are several ways to tell the difference between a magpie and a crow. One easy way is by listening to their song because the sound of a magpie''s call is higher-pitched than that of a similarly sized crow, which has a deeper croak. Another method is looking at their feathers under magnification.</p>
<p>In addition, both birds have different eye shapes: Magpies have larger eyes that are more circular in shape while crows'' eyes are smaller and more triangular-shaped. Finally, magpies tend to be lighter coloured whereas crows usually appear darker brown or black in colouration.</p>
<p><strong>How can you tell what type of bird you''re looking at?</strong></p>
<p>This is a question that people who like birds often ask themselves. The most common method of identifying a bird is by its song, but what if you don''t know the bird''s song? Another way of telling whether it''s a magpie or a crow is to look at their feathers under magnification. Magpies'' feathers are thicker and more rounded, while crows'' are thinner and pointer, just like needles! There are also other ways to tell which bird is what, but this is one of the easiest methods.</p>
<p><strong>What should you do if one lands on your property?</strong></p>
<p>If you are the proud owner of a home or property, you might have one day welcomed your new pet into your yard by feeding it. Little did you know that this magpie or crow could be dangerous! If you''ve found yourself in this situation, never approach the bird with an umbrella because the bird will see the umbrella as a threat. Stay away from cats too because both animals can hurt each other if they feel threatened! Also, crows and magpies aren''t used to being around humans so don''t try to handle them unless absolutely necessary.</p>
<p><strong>Are there any other ways to tell them apart?</strong></p>
<p>In addition, both birds have different eye shapes: Magpies have larger eyes that are more circular in shape while crows'' eyes are smaller and more triangular-shaped. Finally, magpies tend to be lighter coloured whereas crows usually appear darker brown or black in colouration.</p>
<p>Both these birds eat insects, especially during the breeding season, along with nuts and seeds such as oats or corn. They also feed on worms or ants when they go looking for food a second time at night.</p>
<p>If you''re a bird lover, it''s important to know how to differentiate between a magpie and a crow because they can both be dangerous creatures. The best way is by looking at their feathers under magnification or listening carefully for the different sounds of their call. If that doesn''t work, just keep in mind these differences: Magpies have large eyes with round pupils while crows'' are smaller with triangular-shaped pupils; magpies usually appear lighter coloured than crows who tend to look darker brown or black; and finally, magpies feed on insects whereas crows eat more varied food such as worms and oats/corn during the breeding season.</p>', 3, datetime('now') ,'How-to-Tell-a-Magpie-From-a-Crow.jpg'),

(1, 'The History and Use of Magenta in Modern Times', '<p>The history of magenta is not widely known, but its creation opened doors for future innovators to take the colour wheel even further. Now what was once thought of as a "lost" or forgotten colour has made its way into everyday life and pop culture.</p>
<p><strong>What does Magenta mean?</strong></p>
<p>Magenta is the first truly modern synthetic organic colour because it was created by chemists rather than dyes derived from living organisms. It also helped pave the way for other colours like pyrrole red (a type of red), Palatinate Purple (another version of purple) and others.</p>
<p><strong>Where does Magenta come from?</strong></p>
<p>And why might it be called something else? There are several types of magenta including 1-methoxy-2-naphthol, pigment scarlet 4R, 2-[(1-methoxy-2-naphthyl)azo]-1-(p-tolyl)-3 -pyrazolidone or pigment red 122. One of the most common and easiest to use is Pigment Red 122, which is also known as Magenta for its deep shade and vibrance.</p>
<p><strong>What else has magenta been used in?</strong></p>
<p>Magenta was first discovered by accident in 1859 when chemist Jean Baptiste Guimet combined an organic red dye called Pararosaniline (or rosaniline) with Potassium dichromate. His experiments were documented in a thesis after which he shared his findings with other chemists. It was later used to dye silk and the first printed colour advertisements known as colour cards were printed using magenta.</p>
<p><strong>What can you find Magenta in?</strong></p>
<p>Magenta is seen everywhere ranging from clothing, food, art and adverts.</p>
<p><strong>Clothing</strong></p>
<p>Fashion designer Tom Ford released his own lipstick shade called ''Shameless Scarlet'' which was vibrant fuchsia pink inspired by actress Jessica Chastain. He also named it after her because he thought she wore the colour so well.</p>
<p><strong>Food</strong></p>
<p>Jane''s Addiction frontman Perry Farrell has an entire line of wine called "Mod Cerise" (French for "Cherry Mod") that is made up of bright cerise tones; tangerine, grapefruit, bing cherry, pink grapefruit and vanilla.</p>
<p><strong>Art</strong></p>
<p>Magenta has been used by some of the most influential artists in history. The painting ''Wanderer Above the Sea of Fog'' by Casper David Friedrich uses pyrrole red while Mark Rothko used both phthalocyanine green or blue, liquid yellow lemon, liquid light orange, liquid light magenta, alizarin crimson lake extra, phthalocyanine blue, anthraquinone violets lake extra, indanthrone blue, benzimidazolone gold, quinacridone rose and permanent green light.</p>
<p><strong>What is the colour magenta really about?</strong></p>
<p>The colour makes you think of ripe fruits like cherries which are also deep shades of red like Magenta. It''s also associated with the colour pink which is often associated with femininity.</p>
<p><strong>Why was it used in printing?</strong></p>
<p>One of the first printed colour advertisements known as color cards were printed using magenta. Manufacturers began to create fabrics dyed with magenta, scarlet and other bright hues like green to help their products stand out on crowded shelves.</p>
<p><strong>How has it evolved over time?</strong></p>
<p>There are multiple variations of Magenta that can be created especially through digital methods; including Vibrant Pink , Deep Pink, Radiant Fuchsia, Hot Magenta, Ultra Red. Some shades are brighter than others so you''ll notice different tones throughout fashion, clothing, etc.</p>
<p><strong>What does this mean about our culture?</strong></p>
<p>Magenta is a reflection of what we feel and who we are. The vibrant, fiery colour gives us confidence while also meaning innocence or youthful exuberance. It''s a popular choice for parents to help their babies express themselves through clothing because it''s not too loud nor is it boring yet very distinctive.</p>
<p>The history behind magenta makes it clear how this colour has evolved over time while still maintaining its original meaning; making us think about who we are and what we feel inside.</p>', 5, datetime('2021-08-14 02:25:22'), 'The-History-and-Use-of-Magenta-in-Modern-Times.jpg'),

(2, 'Why Do We Talk About Seeing a Magpie at Work?', '<p>Magpies are a symbol of death and bad luck, right? Wrong! In this article, we''ll explore the history of the superstition that if you see a magpie while working, it''s going to be your last day on the job. We''ll also look at some research on how seeing a magpie can actually bring good luck. Let''s get started!</p>
<p>I''ve been working in my office for years now and have never seen a magpie anywhere near me or my workplace. But I''ve read about this superstition many times before so yesterday when I left work early because I had a headache, I made sure to take one last glance around just in case there was an iridescent bird perched nearby. Sure enough, two seconds later I spotted a magpie. Did I get my marching orders? No, surprisingly enough my boss didn''t give me the old heave-ho! But is this a fluke or was she genuinely happy to see me going?</p>
<p>This superstition has been around for centuries and one of the earliest recorded references comes from 1486 when Reginald Peacock wrote: "If you tarry ''til you see, A pye [magpie] upon yonder tree, You need not fear but your master will be good." But what''s strange is that seeing magpies were originally seen as symbols of bad luck - so why did someone decide to turn it upside down? Do any experts know? Actually yes! There are several different theories as to how this superstition came about.</p>
<p>For example, some historians believe it''s because magpies were seen as a symbol of evil omens and would be seen as an omen of doom to those seeing them at work. Others think it all comes from ancient Greece where farmers would kill magpies believing that they harm the fertility of the land and crops that grow on it! However, others believe there''s a hidden message within all this that going for a walk will keep you healthy - which sounds crazy but is true!</p>
<p>But hold on a minute! I''ve never heard anything about going for a walk before? Yes well apparently if you go outside and see two or more magpies then it''s considered good luck. Before I go any further, let''s take a look at some research and see if we can learn anything about seeing magpies in the wild.</p>
<p><strong>What does the research say?</strong></p>
<p>There is plenty of scientific research out there that shows how animals might not be as bad for our health as we believe. For example, researchers from the University of Exeter found that having pets such as dogs and cats help to reduce stress levels in patients who suffer from depression and anxiety. Another study showed that even just looking at cute animal pictures reduces your cortisol levels when placed under stress! So next time you''re feeling stressed why not watch a few videos of puppies playing on YouTube? It might help more than you think! But back to the topic in hand, does seeing magpies really bring good luck?</p>
<p>Well according to the folklore, yes it does! This is because if you see a single magpie then that''s considered unlucky but take a look at two of them and you''re in for some good fortune. But how do we know this? Well if you check out this article on Okehampton Camp you''ll find out how during WW1 an army regiment was stationed there and started hunting magpies to bring them down. Luckily for us, however, they stopped without any casualties so no one was injured yet someone still created an urban myth around the event - which to me sounds like something out of Blackadder Goes Forth!</p>
<p>Another story comes from Manchester where workers would open up a new factory each day. Whenever they heard the chimes of Big Ben, it meant that it was time for them to leave their jobs and look for some magpies - screaming if they found one! But this might be another urban legend because no one has managed to verify this story... yet.</p>
<p><strong>When does this superstition come into play?</strong></p>
<p>The idea is that seeing a single magpie will lead to bad news soon after, but seeing two means you''re in for some great fortune instead. So whenever you see multiple magpies then consider yourself lucky! This includes if you see one magpie while you''re out on a walk or even if you spot one in the wild while taking pictures of wildlife. But was this legend all just hearsay? Or can we actually find any scientific evidence to back it up?</p>
<p>After doing some extensive research online I was surprised that there''s very little evidence to suggest that seeing magpies actually brings good luck - which goes against popular belief. However, after reading through some forums and websites I did manage to come across someone who had personally experienced this superstition for themselves! But before I go into more detail about their story, let''s quickly address some research surrounding animals...</p>
<p><strong>So is there any link between animals and humans health-wise?</strong></p>
<p>Researchers have found time and time again that animals are good for our health and well-being. For example, one study found that people who own pets like cats or dogs could actually live longer than those who don''t because of how they interact with them. The other main reason why seeing magpies brings good fortune is because it means you''ll be healthy soon after - but does this have any scientific links?</p>
<p>Well, I can''t find anything to support this claim but there are numerous studies out there that show us the positive effects pets have on our health. But what about wild animals? What research can we find to back up their benefits to human beings?</p>
<p>Although researchers haven''t found a direct link between seeing magpies and being healthier, there are plenty of academic articles which do back up how we can benefit from seeing most types of wildlife. This includes birds, for example, as one study showed that they play an important role in helping to reduce the number of pests and keep ecosystems healthy. So next time you see a bird or even a magpie while out and about, consider it lucky!</p>
<p>Another superstition which might explain why we talk about seeing magpies is because they can be carrion-eaters - so whenever we see them then it''s possible that someone nearby could have just died! But perhaps there''s another reason as to why this legend came into existence? Let''s now take a look at stories involving magpies...</p>
<p>A few months ago I had my own experience with this superstition, but I didn''t get fired...</p>
<p>I was working in a factory at the time and sometimes we would come across magpies. But hearing them usually meant that it was going to rain - especially if they whistled! The weather forecast proved this theory right, so whenever we heard one then everyone began to run for cover. This only started because someone got struck by lightning while outside which lead us to believe that there must be a link between seeing a magpie and being hit by lightning. But is this actually true?</p>
<p>In fact, although seeing a bird bring bad luck isn''t scientifically proven, scientists have been looking into how animals can predict earthquakes . For example, certain animals such as dogs seem to behave differently before tremors take place and cause concern among those who own them. We also know that other animals have been seen acting erratically just before earthquakes because of how they move their bodies. The only difference between a magpie and a dog, however, is that there doesn''t seem to be any documented cases linking seeing a magpie with being hit by lightning - which might explain why this superstition has died down.</p>
<p>Possible conclusion: 1) Seeing one magpie isn''t going to bring bad luck to you as long as nothing else happens shortly after... 2) But if you see more than one bird then it''s possible that good fortune will follow shortly after... 3) There isn''t enough evidence to suggest that seeing birds brings good health to us or even predicts earthquakes...</p>', 3, datetime('2021-07-08 22:07:43'), 'Why Do We Talk About Seeing a Magpie at Work.jpg'),

(1, 'What Makes the Magenta Colour Scheme Work?', '<p>The magenta colour scheme is a mix of red and violet on the colour wheel. It&rsquo;s said to evoke feelings such as warmth, energy, playfulness, creativity and love.</p>
<p>If you are looking for a colour scheme to use for your company or business logo-magenta might be something to consider! Here''s some more information about what makes it work:</p>
<p><strong>Warmth </strong></p>
<p>Magenta is a warm colour. According to Color Wheel Pro, &ldquo;it&rsquo;s the most energetic of all colours" because it is "neither cool nor warm." This makes it great for evoking feelings that are neither too serious nor too relaxed.</p>
<p>Colours that are similar to magenta in this way include red-violet, pink and burgundy. These hues can be used to give warmth to an image or product design which could evoke feelings of love, playfulness or creativity. &nbsp;</p>
<p>As mentioned above, magenta can also be used as an alternative to red if you are looking for a more feminine colour scheme. It is said that people perceive the colour pink as being warmer than red, even though most people see it as a cooler colour.</p>
<p><strong>Energetic </strong></p>
<p>According to Cool Moose, "Magenta is the colour used by all artists who want to evoke excitement and enthusiasm." This makes sense when you consider that magenta is a mix between red and violet on the colour wheel-two very intense colours.</p>
<p>Dominant hues in your image or logo design can help communicate energy. Magenta is often used along with other bright colours such as yellow and cyan to create high-impact designs. It can be used alternative with pink for a softer feminine look.</p>
<p>A great example of this is the Spotify play button, which has been designed as a combination of magenta and green: two complementary colours.</p>
<p><strong>Creativity </strong></p>
<p>Cool Moose also mentions that "Magenta is the colour of creativity." This may be due to magenta being a mix between red and violet, two hues that are associated with passion and purpose. Magenta has even been used as the official colour of creativity by Adobe Systems because it "reminds us that every great idea comes from thinking outside the box."</p>
<p>This combination could be very useful for designers who are looking for a way to communicate energy without using too much yellow. For example, you could use this color scheme for your business logo if you''re in a creative industry like IT or music: both fields where having an active imagination and taking risks is key to success. &nbsp;</p>
<p>You can also explore this idea in your image and product design by using a dominant magenta hue to represent energy, warmth, creativity or playfulness.</p>
<p><strong>Love </strong></p>
<p>Last but not least, the magenta colour scheme is thought to be associated with love. According to Cool Moose, "People are more relaxed around magenta." This makes it an excellent alternative for red if you are looking for a less competitive or aggressive feel.</p>
<p>The fact that it is made up of two conflicting colours also gives it a playful appeal which could help communicate affection for your audience. For example, baby pink has been shown to have calming properties so it would be perfect for use in marketing campaigns targeting children-especially young girls-or family-related businesses or products.</p>
<p>To conclude, magenta is a great alternative if you are looking for an energetic, but not too aggressive colour scheme. It can be used to evoke feelings of creativity or love and it can also be combined with other hues like pink or cyan to create high-impact designs. &nbsp;The next time you''re designing your company logo, consider magenta as one of the colours in your palette!</p>', 3, datetime('2021-06-07 03:25:37'), 'What-Makes-the-Magenta-Colour-Scheme-Work.jpg'),

(2, 'How Can I Protect My Yard From a Magpie Attack?', '<p>Some people can''t help but feel a sense of dread when they see one of these birds perched on their patio. Others might not think that the magpie is all that bad, and just need to know how to keep them away from your yard.</p>
<p>The purpose of this article is to teach you about the magpies'' habits so you can better protect yourself against them. I''ll also talk about some things you can do if you want to try getting rid of your unwanted visitors for good.</p>
<p>Magpies are some of the most intelligent birds on the planet. They can recognize faces, and some people even think they learn to recognize how much effort you put into scaring them away. It might take them several weeks to start coming back, but don''t lose heart because they will eventually come back.</p>
<p>The magpie is known for its aggressive behaviour where it gets all up in your personal space and encounters little resistance from you, so it keeps doing it more often than not. This happens because humans tend to under-react when it comes to unwelcome confrontations with animals that might lead to an attack, which just encourages the animal''s inappropriate behaviours.</p>
<p>When confronted by this bird, whether it''s perched on your property or trying to poke a beak in your garbage can, always wave your arms and yell at it to indicate you mean business. If the magpie doesn''t get scared away by this point, you should try throwing out something like an empty soda bottle filled with pebbles. This will make enough noise that not only will scare them away but also tell other birds that might think about coming here next time there''s trouble.</p>
<p>If the magpies are getting brave and starting to come around during broad daylight, turn on all of your outdoor lights so they''ll never know what hit them when you go outside with whatever weapon you have on hand. You can also place an owl statue or bird feeder near where the magpies usually hang out. The statue or feeder should be strategically placed so the birds will stare right into it when they try to land in that spot.</p>
<p>If you''re trying to get rid of these birds for good, then there are a few things you can do. It''s probably not very practical to put up an electric fence around your yard, so what most people usually do is string some aluminium pie pans along their fences. The magpies hate the sound the pies make when the wind blows, so they won''t come near your house if they see them. Another thing you can try is tying mylar balloons at ankle height on either side of every entry point where the magpies like to enter and exit your property. These balloons will scare them away just as well as the aluminium pans do.</p>
<p>If you''re concerned for the safety of your pets, then perhaps you should consider keeping them indoors when they''re outside. You can also keep your trashcan inside with a magpie locking lid on it so it''s harder for them to get in and out.</p>
<p>For those whose problem is more severe than just a few birds every now and then, there are companies that have years of experience with humane bird control. If you don''t want to hurt these animals but you want them gone from your property, one of those companies will be able to help by removing them safely from wherever they''re making a nuisance.</p>', 3, datetime('2020-03-30 14:11:25'), 'How-Can-I-Protect-My-Yard-From-a-Magpie-Attack.jpg'),

(1, 'The Psychology Behind the Color Magenta', '<p>The color magenta is a shade of pink that has been used to represent both the artist Prince and the artist&rsquo;s album Purple Rain. The reason for this use stems from his &ldquo;Purple Rain&rdquo; song, which he wrote about how music helped him deal with sadness following his parents&rsquo; divorce. Magenta is also typically associated with creativity. In fact, one study at the University of British Columbia found that participants scored consistently higher on creativity tests when shown different shades of pinks as opposed to other colors such as blue or green. This study concluded that it was specifically because of their association with happiness and creativity.</p>
<p>In light of this research, artists use magenta in order to inspire themselves and others to be creative. The exhibition &ldquo;The Positive Power of Pink&rdquo; at Concordia University in Montreal, Canada was designed to let people express themselves freely through various forms of art. Those artists who participated in the event had their works displayed with specific instructions that they were allowed to use any colors or mediums they wanted.</p>
<p>Magenta is also typically associated with creativity. In one study, participants scored consistently higher on creativity tests when shown different shades of pinks as opposed to other colors such as blue or green. This study concluded that it was specifically because of their association with happiness and creativity. In light of this research, artists use magenta in order to inspire themselves and others to be creative. The exhibition &ldquo;The Positive Power of Pink&rdquo; at Concordia University in Montreal, Canada was designed to let people express themselves freely through various forms of art. Those artists who participated in the event had their works displayed with specific instructions that they were allowed to use any colors or mediums they wanted.</p>
<p>The following references provide information on magenta&rsquo;s association with creativity and its presence within different types of artwork:</p>
