<p>&bull; One study found that participants scored consistently higher on creativity tests when shown different shades of pinks as opposed to other colors such as blue or green. This study concluded that it was specifically because of their association with happiness and creativity: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3338552/.</p>
<p>&bull; Magenta is typically associated with the emotion of happiness, which is why many studies have indicated its presence within paintings portraying human facial expressions: http://sociology.about.com/od/soctermsglossaryf/g/Happiness-Social-Science-Definition-Of-.htm and http://psychologyofwellbeingblog.blogspot.ca/.</p>
<p>The color magenta is used to represent artists Prince and the artist''s album "Purple Rain", which is a reference to the song of that name that he wrote about how music helped him deal with sadness following his parents'' divorce. Magenta is also typically associated with creativity. In fact, one study at the University of British Columbia found that participants scored consistently higher on creativity tests when shown different shades of pinks as opposed to other colors such as blue or green. This study concluded that it was specifically because of their association with happiness and creativity. In light of this research, artists use magenta in order to inspire themselves and others to be creative. The exhibition "The Positive Power of Pink" at Concordia University in Montreal, Canada was designed to let people express themselves freely through various forms of art. Those artists who participated in the event had their works displayed with specific instructions that they were allowed to use any colors or mediums they wanted.</p>', 4, datetime('2021-11-05 05:55:49'), 'The Psychology Behind the Color Magenta.jpg'),

(2, 'Is it OK to eat magpie meat?', '<p>This article will explore the question of whether or not it is OK to eat magpie meat. Eating magpies, also known as pies, has been a part of many different cultures for centuries. Magpies are found all over the world and they are usually consumed in ways that vary from region to region. Some people claim that you can tell if someone is "sweet" by how much they like eating pie. However, some people do not believe it is safe to consume them at all due to their high lead levels which result from their diet of small animals such as rodents and bugs. The truth about this issue may be more complicated than we think though because there have been conflicting studies done on both sides of this debate with no clear answer in sight.</p>
<h2>Environmental Factors</h2>
<p>The environmental factors have played a major role in the studies done on this topic. For example, one study done in Poland showed that the lead levels of pie showed high correlations to the environment they were raised in. A lot of these bugs contain high amounts of lead which they eat and then are then eaten by the pie who absorbs the lead into their systems. However, another study done in Norway showed that pies had low levels of lead in their systems when compared to other wildlife which contradicts this theory.</p>
<h2>It Is Ethical to Eat Magpies</h2>
<p>According to the book "Eating on the Wild Side" by Jo Robinson, magpies are not just safe to eat but they are also high in protein and low in fat. [1] Everyone knows that meat is high in protein due it being an animal product, but most people do not know that plants such as kale and spinach also have protein. It is even possible that the common belief that you need meat to consume protein is incorrect and therefore magpie meat would be an excellent choice for vegetarians. According to the World Health Organization, protein deficiencies are common in developing countries where malnutrition kills more than 3 million children each year. [2] Therefore it may not be horrifically unethical to eat magpies if there is no other option for obtaining protein in these areas of the world. On top of their already healthy nutritional value, wild game such as magpies, rabbits, deer, pheasants, ducks and geese contain much less fat compared to animals raised on farms. "We recommend lean or low-fat meats but there''s an easy way".</p>', 2, datetime('2021-11-05 04:44:53'), 'Is it OK to eat magpie meat.jpg'),

(1, '25 Facts about Magenta', '<p>Good morning! I hope you''ve had a good day. If not, don''t worry--today is the perfect opportunity to start fresh and make it amazing. And here''s 25 facts about magenta to help you get started:</p>
<ol>
<li>Magenta was first discovered when chemists were trying to create quinine from coal tar in 1859</li>
<li>It wasn''t until 1907 that this color was named "magenta" after a French opera called La magie enfantine which tells the story of a little girl who finds a magic box full of paints and uses them to turn her world into a paradise</li>
<li>The American National Standards Institute has standardized on the term &ldquo;magenta&rdquo; for use in designating this color</li>
<li>Magenta was the last of the seven Crayola crayon colors to be introduced in 1958</li>
<li>It''s also known as "primary red", "electric pink" and "deep pink"</li>
<li>Magenta is one of the three secondary colors which are made by mixing primary colors-the other two are blue and green.</li>
<li>The web color magenta is also called fuchsia .</li>
<li>The French impressionist painter Georges Seurat used magenta in many of his paintings, including Sunday Afternoon on La Grande Jatte , an 1884 painting that now hangs at the Art Institute of Chicago.</li>
<li>One company, Pantone, has created a standardized catalog of color palettes, called the PANTONE MATCHING SYSTEM . It has a designated color named "magenta" that''s a blend of 92% red and 88% blue.</li>
<li>In May 2010, scientists at Oregon State University announced they had successfully created magenta fluorescent proteins from shrimp DNA which have potential biomedical applications including being able to quickly detect cadavers so as to prevent unnecessary cholera outbreaks.</li>
<li>The color magenta is also known by the hex triplet #FF00FF or #F0F8FF.</li>
<li>Magenta is associated with creativity, joyfulness , energy , softness, determination , sensuality , passion and sweetness</li>
<li>If you''re looking for a way to create a soft pink look in your space, why not try mixing the colors pink and magenta together.</li>
<li>If your favorite shade of magenta happens to be #FF00FF , you''re in luck! It''s the same color as Dodger blue, Quito blue or Pacific blue.</li>
<li>Have you heard of drum &amp; bass music? Their flag is generally a bright magenta--so if you happen to be a fan of it, keep an eye out for this color!</li>
<li>As with most colors, there are many shades of magenta . For example, there are 47 different shades of red on Adobe''s Kuler website alone.</li>
<li>There are no shades of magenta in HTML/CSS</li>
<li>The first web site to contain any mention of magenta was in March 1997</li>
<li>Magenta is the color scientists believe we''ll be seeing when we look into a black hole</li>
<li>Surrounding yourself with items that are shades of magenta can help to relieve stress and promote inner strength</li>
<li>When paired with white, dark or light gray and black, it creates a look that''s high-fashion , classy and bold.</li>
<li>If you want your brand''s logo to stand out from the crowd, why not consider using magenta for it?</li>
<li>One of the earliest uses of magenta on film was in 1902 by French Lumi&egrave;re brothers who shot several films of workers leaving a spinning dye factory.</li>
<li>The second use was consecutive frames of a rocket launch filmed in slow motion by the German filmmaker Max W. Kimmich and broadcast on February 24, 1935</li>
<li>25) Magenta is color #FF00FF on the web color wheel .</li>
</ol>
<p>I hope you enjoyed these facts! A little magenta can go a long way--so why not add it to your life? If this has inspired you to learn more about magenta then be sure to visit Wikipedia , which was my main source of information for writing this article. Have a good one!</p>
<p>First off, I would like to thank all that are reading this right now. Thank you, thank you, THANK YOU!! You are giving me this opportunity that I never thought would happen again.</p>', 1, datetime('2021-11-05 05:10:11'), '25 Facts about Magenta.jpg'),

(2, 'The Angry Magpie', '<p>"The Angry Magpie" was a ballad that my father used to sing to me when I was a child. He said that the magpie in this song is angry because his songs were never heard by others and only served as background noise. The magpie does not like his songs because they do not bring him joy and he doesn''t want other birds to experience this feeling. This made me sad when I first heard this story, but over time I learned to be grateful for all of my listeners and listeners-to-be who will never hear this song without my telling them about it.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>This ballad is about a magpie who doesn''t like his songs. He decides to go out into the world and sing the same song over and over again in front of other creatures. The poor bird''s aim is to make all of them (and himself) miserable with his incessant, monotonous cries for attention. However, while he does succeed in making everyone else annoyed, they are still oblivious to his presence--all except for one girl who eventually teaches him how important it is to make others happy with your songs by not singing yourself. I think that my father used this story as an analogy for human relationships because he would only sing the first verse and the chorus part of the song otherwise it would get very repetitive.</p>
<p>The lyrics are as follows:</p>
<p>I remember when I was a child, my father used to sing this song for me because he said that it reminded him of me. Now that I''m older, I wonder if the angry magpie''s sentiments about his songs remind him of himself because he never appreciated how hard I worked to make him happy with my singing. And now, perhaps it is too late to apologize for all the selfish thoughts and actions I''ve had throughout our lives together.</p>
<p>My childhood home was very secluded from any other families, so much so that we could not hear any other children playing outside except on sunny days. The closest house where another family lived was at least an acre away (the separating us wasn''t really measured by distance). Our house was surrounded by trees on all sides. There were plenty of children who had previously lived in our neighborhood, but they moved away quickly because of the darkness that seemed to overtake the air around us.</p>
<p>There''s a lot I could blame my father for, some more serious than others. However, one thing is certain; he was always interested in what I would sing and how I sang it (with an emphasis on "it"). He told me stories like this one over and over again until they stuck with me even when I didn''t want them to be remembered anymore. If you asked him about my childhood now, he would say that he wanted me to have music wherever I went--not inside any room or building but in my heart and soul.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>When the magpie begins its singing, an old woman is very annoyed with it and says "O I''m not going to stand this any longer! Here''s a shovel full of ashes; spread them over your back and be done with you!" She goes on to say that she''ll feed him to the pigs if he doesn''t stop his noise, but the magpie continues anyway. An old man tells him to keep quiet as well, but this does not help either. The next morning, when all of the birds are flying around for food they see that one of their own has been covered in ashes from head to toe. They think that he was attacked by some larger and hurry home to tell their families.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The magpie went to see the old man and ask him what happened, but he gets no answer. The magpie goes to the old woman''s house and asks her what had happened and she says that he''d angered her greatly with his singing, so she took out a shovel full of ashes and threw it all over his back. After this discussion, both old people jump into their beds and cover themselves up in sheets pretending that they''re dead just because this one bird came by to talk to them for a few minutes.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Meanwhile, when other birds come home from foraging for food or building nests, they spot the covered-in-ashes magpie who falls down in front of them (he was too tired from his flight to avoid the fall). The magpies rush home and tell their wives and children what they''ve seen and that he must be dead. Once this has reached the ears of the old woman and man, they step outside their houses to see what all the fuss was about. They notice that the ashes have been knocked off of him, which makes them decide to cover themselves in cinders (since it''ll appear as though they died for real). The birds go away again only to return once more with news of another covered-in-ashes magpie near by. This time, both of them jump into a barrel full of water, but after a while they come out because no one is there anymore.</p>
<p>The main conflict in this story is between the old woman, the old man, and the magpie. The old woman doesn''t want to hear his singing anymore while the old man stays quite while he''s present, so he decides it best to leave. It is never mentioned if everything goes back to normal after this point in time.</p>', 5, datetime('2021-11-05 06:08:20'), 'The Angry Magpie.jpg'),

(1, 'What using Magenta lipsticks tells about you and what are the brands to try', '<p>Magenta lipsticks were popularized by pop icon Madonna who often used these color of lipsticks. The use of magenta lipstick has been seen as an act of rebellion against traditional gender roles.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>There are many variations of magenta lipsticks, but it is generally described as a vivid pink-purple color. Magenta lipstick has been associated with power, confidence and individuality.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>A number of notable people have worn this shade including Madonna, Lady Gaga, Rihanna, Beyonc&eacute; Knowles , Jennifer Lopez, Demi Lovato , Christina Aguilera , Nicki Minaj , Lil'' Kim, Rihanna and Lucy Hale .</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The color was explained by Allure in the following way: "The brightest members of the purple family also happen to be some of our favorite fashion muses. The ladies above wear brighter hues like fuchsia and magenta well because they each have very fair skin."</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>In the article "What Your Lipstick Color Says About You, According To Science" by Jessica Ogilvie it was explained that women who wear magenta lipstick tend to have a more positive outlook on life. Also, those same women tend to be more confident and independent then other women.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The color magenta has been associated with individuality and self-expression, as well as being representative of feminism. In an article about pop icon Madonna''s style transformation throughout her career, refinery 29 writes: "As far back as the ''80s she has been challenging gender stereotypes &mdash; from wearing corsets in public to performing in fishnets and conical bras to kissing another woman onstage at the MTV VMAs. She even famously quipped ''Girls can wear jeans and cut their hair short, wear shirts and boots. ''Cause it''s OK to be a boy; But for a girl, stick to dresses and long hair.''"</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The color is often associated with youthfulness. In the article "10 Things Your Lipstick is Telling You" by Dr. Anjali Mahto , she points out that magenta lipstick shades are often worn by young women (especially teenage girls), although there are many exceptions when it comes to certain celebrities who prefer this shade of lipstick.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>In the article "What Your Lipstick Says About You, According To Science" by Jessica Ogilvie it was explained that studies show red lips make women appear more assertive and confident in their ability. When a woman wears a bright shade of lip stick it can give off the impression that she is more sexually available, especially if the color is red. at heart; "I''m not sexy or glamorous. I''m like...serious and dull. But I do want to have a good time, and it''s okay if that makes me look like a weirdo."</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>In the article "What Your Lipstick Says About You" by Allure Magazine, it was explained that studies show red lipstick make women appear more assertive and confident in their ability. This is because of how reds are associated with passion, sexiness, power, confidence, and defiance.</p>
<p>When the color magenta is applied to one''s lips it has been seen as an act of rebellion against traditional gender roles which include staying quiet about your thoughts/opinions. Magenta lipsticks on social media platforms such as Twitter attract attention within feminist communities on social media.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Magenta lipstick brands to try</h2>
<p>As the color of creativity, magenta is making a comeback in cosmetics! Brands are coming out with new colors and formulas for lips, eyes, nails and more. These are some of my favorites:</p>
<p>- Maybelline Vivid Matte Liquid Lipstick in "Violet Underground" - Smashbox Be Legendary Lipstick in "Mint Julep" - Stila Stay All Day Waterproof Liquid Eye Liner Pencil in "Electric Violet" - NYX Professional Makeup Color Jumbo Eyeshadow Palette V2 (Magentic) in "Techno" - NYX Professional Makeup Color Jumbo Eyeshadow Palette V2 (Magentic) in "Metallic Fuchsia"</p>
<p>- Revlon Just Bitten Lipstain + Balm in "Crush" - NYX Liquid Suede Cream Lipstick in "Dare You": http://www.nyxcosmetics.com/p-10-liquid-suede-cream-lipstick.aspx #magenta #purple #lipstick #maybelline #smashbox</p>', 1, datetime('2021-11-05 05:19:18'), 'Magenta lipstick brands to try.jpg'),

(2, 'What is the best way to cook magpies?', '<p>Magpies are excellent for cooking because they have a high amount of protein and also contain fats that help your body absorb the nutrients from other foods. They can be prepared in many ways, including poaching, roasting, baking, frying and stir-frying.</p>
<p>In this post you will find ideas on how to cook magpies as well as some recipes for preparing them. Have fun!</p>
<h2>Magpie Recipes</h2>
<p>Here is a list of recipes for magpies:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Oven Baked Magpie Feathers</strong> &ndash; You will need to clean and remove the feathers from your magpies first. Take out all the insides and rinse with water, then pat dry before oven baking them at 200&deg;C (400&deg;F) for 15 minutes. Remove them from the oven and let cool before eating.</li>
<li><strong>Roasted Magpie</strong> &ndash; Preheat your oven or grill to 170&deg;C (325&deg;F). Wash and clean your magpies thoroughly. Cut off their heads, legs, wings and other unwanted parts. Season with salt and pepper inside their bodies as well as outside. on a roasting tray with a lip, place your magpies breast-side down and bake for 15 minutes.</li>
<li><strong>Stuffed Magpie</strong> &ndash; You can stuff your magpies with a variety of different ingredients such as bread crumbs, bacon rashers, salt and pepper to taste, onion and garlic powder. Combine all the ingredients together and add some water before stuffing them inside their bodies. Bind their legs and wings with string or tie it up with cooking twine so that they don''t fall out while baking in the oven. Cook at 180&deg;C (350&deg;F) for 20 minutes.</li>
<li><strong>Magpie Croquettes</strong> &ndash; Take left-over roasted magpies and mash into a pulp using a fork or pestle on a mortar. Add breadcrumbs, egg and flour into the mixture to help bind it together. Shape your croquettes by rolling them in your hands and coat with bread crumbs before frying for 10 minutes.</li>
<li><strong>Magpie Fricassee</strong> &ndash; This is an excellent dish if you have quite a few magpies on hand. You will need salt and pepper as well as vegetable oil or butter. Clean your magpies thoroughly first before cutting up into pieces including their feet. In a pan, heat a tablespoon of vegetable oil or butter and fry all the pieces until golden brown. Add some water then cover and simmer for about 45 minutes to an hour or until they are tender enough to chew on easily with no sharp bones poking out from the meat.</li>
</ul>', 2, datetime('2021-11-05 04:58:24'), 'What is the best way to cook magpies.jpg'),

(1, 'Ways to use the color magenta in your home', '<p>The color magenta is a fascinating color. It''s a combination of the colors violet and red, two colors which are opposite on the color wheel. Magenta can be used to create soothing or energetic feelings, depending on its shade. The darker shades will usually have more energy while lighter shades will have more calming effects.</p>
<p>In this post we''ll cover some ways you can use magenta in your home decorating scheme. First let''s start with an easy way: pillows! There are plenty of variations out there for magenta pillows; from simple solid colors to complex patterns and prints like paisley and damask designs. If you want something even simpler than that, try using a traditional white pillowcase with a piece of fabric that matches your d&eacute;cor on top.</p>
<p>Another simple way to use magenta in your home is by painting one wall of a room. This can be either the walls facing each other if you have an open floor plan, or the back wall of the room you are decorating.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>You could also try painting some cabinets or cupboards in magenta instead of black, white, grey or rustic browns . It''s bright enough that it will create a good contrast with dark colors while being interesting enough without becoming too distracting. If you''re really looking for something bold then why not paint all your appliances magenta? A stove, fridge and dishwasher can liven up any kitchen or dining area!</p>
<p>For another bold design move, you could paint the floor in your living room magenta! This is a design trick that has been used by interior designers for decades. Sometimes it can be hard to decorate around large pieces of furniture like couches, chairs and cabinets; painting the floor creates the illusion that they are not there, allowing your imagination to be free while at the same time creating bold focal points.</p>
<p>Finally let''s mention one more way to use magenta in your home. You may have seen this technique before; sewing contrasting fabric strips on either side of your couch or some other seating area... if you haven''t done this already then try it out some time. It works really well with red, green or black fabrics but can also look good with more muted colors like beige, taupe or white.</p>
<p>If you want to learn more about decorating with magenta then please visit this page . On that site I discuss other ways to use the color magenta in your home. There are even some pictures of rooms decorated in magenta for inspiration!</p>', 1, datetime('2021-11-05 05:22:07'), 'Ways to use the color magenta in your home.jpg'),

(2, 'Magpie Recipe Ideas', '<p>Magpies are not the most popular birds, but they may be among the smartest. Recent research shows that magpies can understand cause-and-effect relationships and anticipate future events based on past experience. When they see a person hide food in one location, for example, they know it''s likely to happen again in another location.</p>
<p>This makes them ideal companions for cooks who need help keeping track of what needs to go into the oven next or how much time is left until dinner is ready!</p>
<p>It also means that it pays to take care when you''re cooking with magpies around! They''ll notice if you accidentally leave something out of your recipe or forget an important step in preparing your dish. If you want to keep them from messing up your cooking, here are some ideas:</p>
<p>- Magpies can''t taste anything, so they don''t care if their food is spicy. If you''ve tried a dish with magpie and found it''s too spicy for your tastes, try adding more of the foods you commonly cook with to balance out the flavor.</p>
<p>- If you want to give one of them a healthy snack but don''t know how it will go over, ask if they''d like a sample before feeding them an entire meal! Also, see what types of berries or nuts they might be interested in collecting. Letting them know that certain plants are poisonous may cause problems - they''ll avoid those plants and never find out which ones make good snacks.</p>
<p>Magpies are also very curious. If you''re trying to keep one out of your kitchen, be sure to put locks on all the cabinets and drawers! They''ll check them all if they can, so make sure nothing is left open by mistake.</p>
<p>- Do not leave any food outside where it might attract magpies.</p>
<p>- Ensure that no magpie can sneak up behind you or trap you in a corner - they may try to take advantage of your distraction by stealing something. If necessary, pick up small objects like utensils before cooking with magpies around.</p>
<p>- Magpies can open jars and cans easily, even without opposable thumbs. these types of containers well away from where you''re cooking to avoid any accidents.</p>
<p>- Magpies may try to eat things that aren''t food! Keep a close eye on them and enforce safe eating habits if they get into your chemicals/medicine cabinet, toiletries, etc.</p>
<p>- If you''re near a body of water such as a river or ocean, feed the magpie something substantial before heading in - they might decide to go fishing with their bare hands! This can be entertaining for both of you, but could lead to dangerous situations.</p>
<p>Now that we know how to handle these types of problems, it''s time for some recipe ideas:</p>
<p>1) Spicy Potatoes and Maggot Stew:&nbsp;&nbsp; (potatoes, butter) + (nightcrawler, salt)</p>
<p>2) Sweet Magpie Pie: (handful of mixed dried berries, pie crust) + (magpie, cinnamon)</p>
<p>3) Magpie Mac&amp;Cheese: (fresh maggots in the garden, butter knife to scrape them off, macaroni noodles; boiling water; cheese slices; + maggie(s))</p>
<p>4) Tree Rat Surprise (tree rat fillets in foil with lemon juice and chopped vegetables like carrots or potatoes), + two or more magpies. Tip: If you want to be sure it''s safe to eat before letting your magpies try it, make tree rat surprise for yourself first! This dish is very healthy and has a lot of protein - if your magpies eat it up, they must have liked it.</p>
<p>See? Cooking with Magpies isn''t so hard! Keeping them out of the kitchen is a little harder though - good luck and happy cooking!</p>
<p>(For a complete list of references and citations for this article, email magpieeaterbob@gmail.com)</p>', 2, datetime('2021-11-05 04:58:24'), 'Magpie Recipe Ideas.jpg'),

(1, 'Is there such thing as a fetish with the color magenta?', '<p>Is there such thing as a fetish with the color magenta? I don''t know. But, I can tell you that if there is, then this blog post might be just for them!</p>
<p>I''m not sure whether or not it''s possible to have a "magenta fetish", but now that the question has been posed...it seems like an interesting topic to explore. If you do happen to have one of these rare fetishes, then please feel free to share your thoughts in the comment section below!</p>
<p>I''m going to take a bit of an artistic approach for this blog post, where I''ll explore the various uses and meanings associated with the color magenta.</p>
<p><strong>The "Crayola" Color Magenta!</strong></p>
<p>A little background on how this subject came to my attention...</p>
<p>During my research for yesterday''s post about how to wear red lipstick, I stumbled upon a site that listed all the different color names used in crayons. When I saw "magenta", it caught my eye because when you hear the word "magenta", many think of purple. In reality however, magenta is a pinkish-red hue that is commonly associated with pinks and purples in crayons. If you look at the picture above, it''s easy to see that there''s hardly any difference between magenta and purple!</p>
<p><strong>A Little Bit of History...</strong></p>
<p>As with most colors, magenta wasn''t always just a color in crayons! Like red-violet (magenta), this color was known as "fuschine" at one point in time. Originally, Fuschine&mdash;a dye extracted from lichen&mdash;was discovered around 1859 by an Italian chemist who named the substance after his homeland of Fusch, Austria.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Before its discovery as a dyestuff (the definition of which is simply "...substances that can be used for dyeing"), Fuschine was commonly used in medicines and cosmetics. But, once chemists created synthetic dyes during the late 1800''s...Fuschine began to lose its popularity as a dye. (However, it still gained some notoriety because of the fact that Fuschine could be easily obtained from lichen).</p>
<p><strong>The Color Magenta Today!</strong></p>
<p>Today, magenta is still widely used in medicine and cosmetics; but, there are very few commercial uses for this color due to the fact that so many artificial dyes exist today. Thusly, today people use "magenta" when referring to anything with slight reddish-purplish undertones&mdash;just like what you see in crayons. In modern times, the word "magenta" isn''t often used to describe a color...but when it is, you can trust that it''s quite close to being a purplish-red shade!</p>
<p><strong>The Color Magenta in Popular Culture</strong></p>
<p>Most people know that in pop culture, magenta is usually associated with purple. But have you ever heard of a song called "Magenta?" Well if you haven''t I''m going to tell you about it anyway! Released back in 1984 as part of an album by David Bowie, "Magenta" describes something as being "...like an animal." In other words, magenta suggests something primal and untamed&mdash;something dangerous but fascinating at the same time. However, this is somewhat ironic because magenta isn''t typically associated with danger...</p>
<p><strong>Types of Magenta!</strong></p>
<p>Now that you have a better understanding of what the color "magenta" means today, let''s look at other shades related to it. Keep in mind, there are plenty of different variations of magenta for you to choose from&mdash;some being very light and others being quite dark.</p>
<p><strong>What Colors Go Well With Magenta?</strong></p>
<p>Just like most other colors, purple compliments magenta nicely! However, I think that pink goes even better with magenta than purple does! So if you''re ever shopping for makeup or clothes...or if you''re simply looking for something new to put on your walls, don''t be afraid to experiment with different shades of magenta.</p>
<p><strong>Magenta (Music)</strong></p>
<p>Today, all types of music genres use magenta when describing something that''s considered very hip or in-style. For example, when people say that a certain type of dance music is "very magenta," they''re basically saying that it sounds really good! (Of course, this isn''t necessarily true in every caseIs there such thing as a fetish with the color magenta?</p>', 4, datetime('2021-11-05 05:39:47'), 'Is there such thing as a fetish with the color magenta.jpg'),

(2, 'What should you do if a magpie attacks?', '<p>Do you know what to do if a magpie attacks? The answer may astound you. It&rsquo;s not as simple as it seems. In fact, the best course of action is often counterintuitive.</p>
<p>What should I do if a magpie attacks me? Does this sound like an annoying joke that someone made up just to annoy people who are afraid of birds? Well, bird expert David FitzSimmons would tell you otherwise: &ldquo;If a bird hits you, there''s no need to panic or try and shoo it away." He goes on to explain that "most birds will fly off after they''ve hit somebody" and that "they''re usually only trying to protect their nest." So next time one of these little demons honks into you, just chill and let it be. It knows what it does.</p>
<p>Difficult as it may seem, we must implore you: Do not run after the bird with your arms flapping frantically. If they are still attacking an hour later, they are most likely nesting nearby . At this point, making a large amount of noise getting away is best advised. Make sure that you don''t have any food with you at all times to avoid further attacks during this time! This includes pockets! With these tips in mind, Australia''s magpie population will be kept under control for years to come!</p>
<p>Still unsure about what to do if a magpie attacks? See below for further information about my personal experiences with these diabolical birds.</p>
<p>I remember this one time when I was just minding my own business, walking along the street on my way to work. All of a sudden, out of nowhere, this godawful squawking sound assaults my ears as something crashes directly into me. The pain is incredible! My body is wracked with agony! I think it''s safe to say that this horrible incident would have killed most other people - but not tough ol'' Davey Whelan here! After the searing pain subsided enough for me to catch my breath, I realized that all the commotion had attracted quite an audience. People were clapping and cheering me on as if some sort of witch doctor b-grade movie was unfolding before them! Just when I thought that things couldn''t get any worse, the magpie came back for a second attack. This time however, it swooped down on my face and pecked out one of my eyeballs. Fortunately for me, my other eye was still intact so I managed to escape with only minor disfigurement.</p>
<p>A few months after this incident had taken place, some loony bloke called me up claiming that he could lead me to the nest where the bird had come from. I laughed at him at first - but eventually got curious enough to go along with him anyway. Well let me tell you something kiddies - judging by all of the eggs in that nest, there must have been at LEAST ten thousand maggies running around out there! Something had to be done about this! I went back into the wilderness that very same night and hunted down every last one of those vile creatures. Finally, all was quiet again in my neighbourhood.</p>
<p>Still not sure what to do if a magpie attacks you? Maybe these pictures will sway your opinion:</p>
<p>-Dave Whelan (Not the footballer guy)</p>
<p>Sources: <a href="http://www.birdcoop.com/pages/magpie_facts%20http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/pdf/Magpie_Booklet_BIN105S1%5BMkU4NjA0OTIzMzI">http://www.birdcoop.com/pages/magpie_facts http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/pdf/Magpie_Booklet_BIN105S1%5BMkU4NjA0OTIzMzI</a></p>', 5, datetime('2021-11-05 06:13:49'), 'What should you do if a magpie attacks.jpg'),

(1, '10 ways the color magenta affects your mood', '<p>The color magenta has many effects on your mood. Here are 10 of them!</p>
<p>1. Magenta is the perfect balance between red and violet, which makes it a great way to increase energy or relax after a stressful day at work</p>
<p>2. People who wear clothes in this color tend to be more extroverted than people who don''t (although they might not know why!)</p>
<p>3. It''s no coincidence that pink is often used as an act of love - magenta stimulates the release of dopamine, oxytocin, and serotonin.</p>
<p>4. The power of magenta can also be found in food: some studies show that eating foods with this color could help lower blood pressure and cholesterol levels while increasing weight loss rates by up to 10%.</p>
<p>5. When exposed to a magenta light, the brain responds by releasing a chemical that stimulates your memory and creative thinking skills!</p>
<p>6. This color is used in many creative industries, including fashion design and interior design - which could have an effect on mood as well as productivity!</p>
<p>7. Magenta can also help relieve stress from electronic devices such as phones and computers - this is because the color acts as a natural anti-inflammatory agent.</p>
<p>8. In addition, it can improve your appetite by increasing your stomach''s production of digestive juices!</p>
<p>9. The calming effects of this color make it great for those who suffer from migraines or eye strain!</p>
<p>10. It has been proven that a room in magenta can lower heart rate, pulse rate, and blood pressure!</p>', 4, datetime('2021-11-05 05:48:13'), '10 ways the color magenta affects your mood.jpg'),

(2, 'The downside of magpie taxidermy', '<p>The downside of magpie taxidermy is that it can be difficult to find the right parts. There are plenty of dead animals out there, but not all of them make good additions to your home decor. It&rsquo;s important to know what you want beforehand and then search for it specifically. For example, if you like the look of a deer head mounted on your wall, don&rsquo;t go around looking for anything with antlers because odds are nothing will work out; you should only be searching for deer heads in order to get what you want. The best way to do this is by finding pictures online or in magazines and taking note of where they came from so that when the time comes, hopefully sooner than later, you will have an easier time finding dead animals to suit your needs.</p>
<p>Once you&rsquo;ve found the parts that you want, it&rsquo;s also good to know when is the best time in which to bring home your latest additions. Certain seasons are better than others when it comes to hunting for certain animal parts; once again, taking note of when these times occur is vital when hunting down dead animals. For example, even though you might find several deer heads in the summer, there is a much greater chance of finding buck heads in the fall. The same can be said about foxes or rabbits etc.; just Google search &ldquo;when to hunt for [insert animal here] heads&rdquo; and you should get some pretty accurate results depending on where you&rsquo;re located.</p>
<p>The best time to go out and find something, dead or alive, is during the night or early morning hours. Generally speaking this is when most animals are on the move so you increase your chances of finding something by being out at these times of day. If possible try not to have anything scheduled for after 9 pm so that you can enjoy some good old-fashioned nightime hunting; if you do go out before sunset it&rsquo;s always a good idea to take a headlamp with you because nothing ruins a good walk like getting caught in the dark and having no way of seeing where you&rsquo;re going.</p>
<p>A final concern would be how much money one should spend on taxidermy. No matter what you like or what your tastes are, it&rsquo;s never easy to drop a couple hundred bucks on something without knowing how long it will last; this is where building up an emergency fund comes in handy. Try not to overspend because if you do and end up hating whatever it is that you get, you&rsquo;ll be stuck with it for the rest of your life which could result in unwanted frustration. If needed, try taking out a little bit of cash every week until you reach whatever amount seems right for whatever type of animal part that you want. It might seem like too much at first but when compared to the joy that comes from finally bringing home your latest addition then I think any minor inconveniences are worth getting there faster.</p>
<p>The &lsquo;art&rsquo; of magpie taxidermy may seem like it can be difficult at first but when broken down into simple steps it becomes something that anybody can do. All that is needed are the right parts, the right tools, and a little bit of patience. Once these things have been found then you should go out there and find yourself some dead animals! Good luck to all who partake in this rewarding hobby!</p>', 5, datetime('2021-11-05 06:21:24'), 'The downside of magpie taxidermy.jpg'),

(1, 'Why magenta is the perfect color for your logo', '<p>It&rsquo;s the color of royalty! It has a strong history in art and design. And it can be used to make your logo pop. So why is magenta still not as popular as blue?</p>
<p>Magenta is an amazing color with lots of benefits, but unfortunately there are some misconceptions about its meaning that keep people from using it more often. Let&rsquo;s take a look at what those myths are and how you can overcome them to use the power of magenta for good!</p>
<p><strong>Myth #1: Magenta is just pink</strong></p>
<p>Nope! True magenta is a strong, vibrant color that has blue undertones. It&rsquo;s the perfect middle ground between cool blue and warm red. Like this lovely color swatch from Color Wheel Pro .</p>
<p>And if you use pure magenta it will end up looking like an intense red on your website or in print. There is nothing wrong with using red in your logo design. But you can make it more unique by adding a little bit of magenta to create something fresh and unexpected.</p>
<p><strong>Myth #2: Magenta is too girly</strong></p>
<p>OK, so this myth really depends on how you are using the color...if there are multiple used in your logo design, and they are all the soft shades of pink, you could be unintentionally creating a feminine look.</p>
<p>But if you use a stronger magenta as one of your main colors for your logo design it will project strength and confidence. And that is a very manly thing to do! So this myth can be put to rest with just a little bit of color theory knowledge.</p>
<p><strong>Myth #3: Magenta has no meaning</strong></p>
<p>This isn&rsquo;t true either! The strong shade of magenta was named after Magnesia , an ancient region in Greece known for its rich deposits of the mineral porcelain clay called &ldquo;Magnesian Chalk&rdquo; which was used as pigment by painters for thousands of years. In fact, the first recorded use of magenta as a color name in English was back in 1859 A.D., according to Dictionary.com , making it one of the newest color terms on their list!</p>
<p>Now that you know some of the history of this vibrant hue, here are two examples where magenta has been used for some awesome logo designs:</p>
<p>Excited about using magenta for your logo design? We think you will love these rich shades from our friends at Cheap4ink</p>
<p>Red River Paper is known for its unique printing capabilities and great prices. So who could be better than them to show off how beautiful magenta can look in print! Check out how they use magenta on their website here .</p>
<p>So there you have it! Magenta is not just for girls or people that are into astrology. It&rsquo;s a powerful color with an important place in the history of art and design, perfect for making your logo stand out from the crowd.</p>
<p>Now get to work creating something spectacular!</p>', 2, datetime('2021-11-05 06:28:49'), 'Why magenta is the perfect color for your logo.jpg'),

(2, 'Magpies in the media', '<p>The Australian magpie is commonly found in around 80-90% of the continent. They are known to be territorial birds and are found in both rural and urban areas. The black and white bird with a red beak is not only seen throughout the country but also found in media all over the world. The Australian magpie has been featured in movies, cartoons, games, songs, artwork, tattoos, TV commercials, books, magazines and even tattoos - to name a few examples.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The Australian magpie is commonly displayed in different styles of artwork, but one frequently appearing design is the tattoo of the bird flying with another creature (usually a kangaroo, emu etc) in its claws. This design can be seen all around the world and it''s often mistakenly believed that this design has some sort of tribal significance, but it doesn''t. It dates back to at least the early 19th century when bushmen would paint these symbols on their bodies to show what they''ve hunted or found during a trip into the wilderness. The designs were usually exaggerated as this helped identify them from a distance. In some cases these drawings also included small human figures, lizards or flowers - each had a meaning too which told something about the person. The bird with prey design was used to show that they were adept hunters and skilled at snaring their prey. Brumbies (wild horses) are sometimes seen instead of kangaroo''s in these drawings, as the horse is an introduced species in Australia. This "bush tat" was also popular for a time among prisoners; especially those who had spent some time out bush where they lived off the land with minimal supplies. As thousands of convicts were sent to Australia during early colonial days it made sense that many would have created these images on their bodies to convey what sort of life they used to live or how well adapted they were to this wild country.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The Australian magpie tattoo has never had any tribal meaning attached to it, nor is the bird considered to be sacred or significant in any way. This tattoo design is purely based on widespread pop culture imagery which has been used for decades. The image dates back to at least the 1930s when it was seen on postcards and was also printed on hats during this era too. The magpie''s popularity continued through to the 1950s and 1960s when they were seen all over TV shows, movies, comics - even blatantly racist images of "Minstrel Shows" also featured them. You can see one such hideous portrayal below (please don''t laugh at the black face!) that came via US TV show Amos &amp; Andy - a popular sitcom from 1953-1956.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Australian magpie tattoos are commonly seen on the arms and legs of both men and women. It is not unusual to see them tattooed all over a person, as they can be placed in any position like other animal designs. This bird sits beautifully for a shoulder piece and can also suit many different body parts (front and back pieces etc) . Their popularity has now spread to Europe too, where several countries have now adopted this iconic Australian image as their own.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The magpie is mostly seen with its head turned backwards like it''s about to say "cheerio" - but there are some artists who prefer illustrating it as if it''s staring at you or everyone else around you. A lot of contemporary artists will reduce the black details in the wings which means that the design appears lighter and more subtle, while some go to the other extreme and feature it in black &amp; white or sepia. There''s not one particular way of depicting this bird and there is still a lot room for creativity when it comes to how it should look - but most stick with what feels right and won''t alter the design too much from its original form, as that defeats the purpose of why someone would get such a tattoo in the first place!</p>', 3, datetime('2021-11-05 06:35:45'), 'Magpies in the media.jpg'),

(1, 'What does it mean when someone is wearing magenta?', '<p>The color magenta is a mixture of red and violet. It has the same hue as rose, but with less saturation. The name comes from the Latin "magenta" meaning either "dark purple" or "brilliant scarlet". Magenta was first introduced commercially in 1859 by two French chemists who had discovered that mixing aniline dye with sulfuric acid, potassium bichromate, and water produces a substance which colors cloth deep purple-red. This process was popularized under the names ''aniline black'' or ''fuchsine''. But it wasn''t until 1908 when magenta became widely used for its modern purpose of printing colored images on paper after being patented by George Rudge who originally sold magenta-colored socks.</p>
<p>So if someone is wearing magenta, what does that mean? As stated above, the color magenta is a mixture of red and violet. It has the same hue as rose, but with less saturation. When one wears magenta it simply means they are wearing an article of clothing which contains this particular color. That''s pretty straight forward.</p>
<p>Where did tumblr get off claiming if you wear magenta clothes you are gay ?</p>
<p>What an odd generalization to make... Like many other generalizations posted by tumblr users about colors (i.e black being evil), it lacks concrete evidence, therefore cannot be true; unless you''re making some sort of subliminal message out of your fashion choice? Here''s some evidence from the web on why magenta is not a homosexual color:</p>
<p>In fashion, wearing pink means you''re gay. In fashion, wearing anything that isn''t black or grey means you''re gay. In fashion, being visible and having a pulse means you''re gay.</p>
<p>For men who want to avoid this fashion rule &ndash; assume it''s true &ndash; there are several ways around it &ndash; for instance, green &ndash; which is also considered a feminine colour for guys if your wardrobe consists of pink shirts and green pants, then all I can say is good luck with that whole straight thing&hellip;" -Rennie Dyball</p>
<p>Wearing Magenta Doesn''t Make You Gay... Wearing Anything That Isn''t Black Or Grey Does... by snickerpants</p>
<p>So if you wear magenta clothes or any other color, relax. You might just be expressing yourself by wearing the color of your choice. Personally I think wearing pink (for guys) would look pretty good on some people... but that''s just me :)</p>
<p>This blog is not meant to discredit religion in anyway! All religious beliefs are welcome here.</p>', 5, datetime('2021-11-05 06:01:30'), 'What does it mean when someone is wearing magenta.jpg'),

(2, 'Why Magpies are Popular in Fairy Tales', '<p>Magpies are mid-sized songbirds with black and white plumage. The head, neck, tail, wings and back are black while the rest of their body is white. This combination gives them an appearance that makes them look like they are wearing a tuxedo, making them very popular in films, films and paintings. It is said that the dark spots on their white plumage are reminiscent of eyes, so they have been linked to the notion of magic and mystery throughout history.</p>
<p>The English word magpie comes from the Latin "pica", which itself comes from the earlier Greek &pi;?&sigma;&chi;&omicron;&sigmaf; piskos, meaning ''seed-eating bird''. The magpie is therefore not a bird native to Great Britain but has occupied the role of a pest that steals small shiny things from everyone here. In China, however, it is considered a good omen because its white colour symbolizes joy and gratitude.</p>
<p>The collective noun for a group of magpies is a "murder" of magpies.</p>
<p><strong>What roles do they play in fairy tales?</strong></p>
<p>Magpies are extremely popular birds that have appeared in countless stories, legends and superstitions since ancient times. They are typically portrayed as intelligent birds that could understand human speech, but they were also linked to omens of death.</p>
<p>A tale by the Brothers Grimm tells about a vain and foolish young man who wants to impress his lover with tricks that he learned from magpies. Magpies had been known for many years through tales like this one, which made them some of the most famous birds in the animal kingdom.</p>
<p>Superstitions about magpies are very varied across different European countries, but they usually range from good luck to bad luck depending on actions that people took with regard to them. Magpies were sometimes described as thieves who liked shiny objects like jewellery, so it is perhaps not surprising that these birds inspired many fairy tales.</p>
<p><strong>How are they related to the crows?</strong></p>
<p>Magpies and crows belong to the order of Corvus birds, which also includes jays, ravens and jackdaws. The magpie is often confused with a crow or even a raven because these species are very similar in appearance. In general, however, magpies tend to be shinier and have longer tails than other corvid species.</p>
<p><strong>Are there similar species of birds?</strong></p>
<p>A lot of birds have black and white plumage that makes them look similar to magpies. Examples include the grackle, jaybird, myna bird, jackdaw and rook.</p>
<p>There are around 120 known species in the Corvidae family. This figure includes Hawaiian crows and ground-living crows that live on Fiji and other Pacific islands. These birds are generally smaller than most corvids, but they share a very similar appearance.</p>
<p><strong>Conclusion</strong></p>
<p>Magpies are a popular bird in fairy tales and stories because of their black and white plumage. They were seen as intelligent birds who could understand human speech or omens of death depending on the story. Magpie superstitions vary across different European countries, but they''re mostly considered good luck if you harm them with bad luck coming to those that tease them for being thieves by stealing shiny objects like jewels.</p>
<p>If you find yourself surrounded by magpies, it''s best not to go near them! You''ll also be interested to know that there is no such thing as an English magpie - these corvids originated from China and migrated over through Europe centuries ago where they became pests!</p>', 4, datetime('2021-05-21 07:46:02'), 'Why-Magpies-are-Popular-in-Fairy-Tales.jpg'),

(1, 'Magenta: The perfect color for any occasion?', '<p>The world is full of colors. We all know the basics ones, but have you ever considered what color would be perfect for any occasion? I&rsquo;ve found one that fits so many occasions it might become your new favorite. Magenta! Read on to learn about this fabulous color and why it&rsquo;s so versatile.</p>
<p><strong>Magenta: A Color of Many Uses</strong></p>
<p>Ranging in hue from deep red to bluish purple, magenta is a color with quite an array of uses. Even though it&rsquo;s most commonly associated with the 80s and 90s when magenta was used in branding (I can say that because I remember them well), this versatile hue has many modern applications.</p>
<p>Why magenta? Because no matter what type of event you&rsquo;re planning&mdash;a wedding, a baby shower, a birthday party&mdash;it&rsquo;ll fit right in and add flair! As we delve into your many options, let''s start with weddings! Here are some great ideas for how to incorporate magenta.</p>
<p><strong>MAGENTA AT YOUR WEDDING</strong></p>
<p>Weddings are full of important moments to commemorate, so why not use magenta to do it? From invitations and save-the-dates to menu cards (and even confetti), there&rsquo;s no shortage of opportunities. Of course, the major ones are your dress and flowers, which you can customize to be magenta or pink . That way, everything ties together into one amazing color scheme. Just imagine how beautiful they&rsquo;ll look on your big day! (See some options here .)</p>
<p>Now that you know about how awesome magenta is for weddings, let&rsquo;s move on to another popular event: baby showers ! Here''s how you can make it work for this joyous occasion.</p>
<p><strong>MAGENTA AT YOUR BABY SHOWER</strong> You know what they say: pink is the new blue . In this case, magenta combines perfectly with baby blues to make a super-sweet color scheme for your baby shower. That way, you&rsquo;ll be able to create special invitations and decorations that match the theme of your event without sacrificing style or personality. With so many other details to take care of besides just invitations, it can be a relief knowing that one element lays all the groundwork&mdash;and looks great doing it! If you&rsquo;re not sure which shade of magenta will best match your baby shower''s vibe, find inspiration from things around you, such fabric patterns , tie dye , or art.</p>
<p>If you&rsquo;re looking for even more uses of magenta, don''t worry! We have a few more in store for you to help plan your next party. Let''s continue with some decorating ideas now.</p>
<p><strong>MAGENTA IN YOUR HOME</strong></p>
<p>Whether you love a bold pop of color or prefer a subtler approach, there are so many ways magenta can enhance your space&mdash;and not just by slapping it on the walls . Give yourself an extra level of creativity by incorporating this fabulous hue into your d&eacute;cor as much as possible&mdash;both for now and later as it matures with you. For example&hellip; Try out different types of lighting , from table lamps to paper lanterns to string lights . Add an element of whimsy with magenta light fixtures . Frame your favorite photos in magenta to create a special display. If you&rsquo;re feeling extra adventurous, paint one wall magenta and see how it changes the look of your space!</p>
<p>If you want some ideas for what types of d&eacute;cor to use with your magenta wall, check out our article on color-themed party decorations !</p>
<p>Now that we&rsquo;ve looked at some fun ways to incorporate this happy hue into events big and small, let''s get back to why everyone loves it so much. Ready? Here are five reasons why people get excited over this color!</p>
<p><strong>WHY IS MAGENTA POPULAR?</strong> Now that you know all about this vibrant shade, you may have some questions about what&rsquo;s so amazing about it. If you''re on board with magenta, great! But if not yet, why not? There are a few theories out there as to how people first came around to loving this color. One is that it has a way of slowing time down . People say the world feels right when they see...</p>', 1, datetime('2021-11-05 07:51:40'), 'Magenta The perfect color for any occasion.jpg');

